Claims CLAIMS We claim: 1 . A structurally integrateable lighting system comprising: a structural member having a top surface, a bottom surface and a longitudinal axis, said bottom surface configured to receive at least one optical light source; a heat sink connected to said structural member top surface and thermally connected to said structural member bottom surface, wherein said heat sink comprises a plurality of heat dissipating elements with a heat dissipating element longitudinal axis substantially aligned with said structural member longitudinal axis; and a surface support formed from a portion of said structural member top surface configured to support a ceiling panel; or a ceiling panel receiving slot operably connected to the structural member and configured to receive a ceiling panel. 2. The system of claim 1 , further comprising: an optical light module comprising said at least one optical light source connected to said structural member bottom surface and in thermal contact with said heat sink; wherein said optical light source comprises one or more light emitting diodes (LED). 3. The system of claim 1 , wherein the ceiling panel comprises a first panel and a second panel, wherein: said surface support has a first support portion configured to receive said first panel and a second support portion configured to receive said second panel; said first support portion is positioned along a first outer longitudinal edge of said structural member; and said second support portion is positioned along a second outer longitudinal edge of said structural member so that said structural member is configured to extend between and support said first panel and said second panel, wherein each support portion has a surface area in contact with a ceiling panel that is between 1 cm 2 and 50 cm 2 . 4. The system of claim 3, wherein at least a portion of the ceiling panel is optically transparent, at least a portion of the structural member is optically transparent, or both at least a portion of the structural member and the ceiling panel are optically transparent. 5. The system of claim 1 , wherein said ceiling panel is optically opaque. 6. The system of claim 1 , wherein said structural member has a width that is greater than or equal to 1 cm and less than or equal to 20 cm. 7. The system of claim 1 , wherein said structural member comprises a thermally conductive material comprising aluminum, iron, steel, copper, carbon fiber, or a combination thereof. 8. The system of claim 1 wherein the structural member further comprises a cover fastener connected to said bottom surface configured to fasten a cover to said structural member. 9. The system of claim 8, wherein said cover fastener comprises: a first clasp extending from said bottom surface; a second clasp extending from said bottom surface, wherein said first and second clasps are separated from each other by a cover separation distance sufficient to receive one or more optical light sources. 10. The system of claim 9, wherein said first clasp and said second clasp extend an entire length of said structural member, or comprise a plurality of paired clasps, with adjacent pairs of clasps separated from each other by a cover longitudinal distance. 1 1 . The system of claim 8 further comprising a cover connected to said cover fastener, said cover configured to surround a plurality of optical light sources of said optical light module and to disperse light emitted from said plurality of optical light sources in a direction away from said structural member. 12. The system of claim 1 1 , wherein said cover is a lens or a diffuser. 13. The system of claim 1 wherein said structural member further comprises a cable conduit formed from said structural member top surface, said cable conduit having a conduit longitudinal axis. 14. The system of claim 13, wherein said conduit longitudinal axis is substantially aligned with said structural member longitudinal axis. 15. The system of claim 13, wherein said cable conduit further comprises: an outer cable conduit member extending from said structural member top surface; and an inner cable conduit member extending from said structural member top surface and separated from said outer cable conduit member by a cable conduit width to form said cable conduit from an inner surface of said outer cable conduit member, said structural member top surface, and an outer 

 surface of said inner cable conduit member, wherein said cable conduit is positioned on an outer portion of said structural member top surface. 16. The system of claim 15, further comprising a second cable conduit positioned on a second outer portion that is opposibly positioned to said outer portion, wherein said heat sink is positioned in an inner region of said structural member top surface formed between an inner surface of said inner cable conduit member and an inner surface of said second inner cable conduit member. 17. The system of claim 16, wherein said inner cable conduit members have a distal end further comprising a mounting slot configured to receive a fastener. 18. The system of claim 17, wherein said mounting slot is a threaded opening for receiving a screw for reliably positioning one or more of: a driver, a ballast, an adapter, a fan, or a power supply. 19. The system of claim 1 further comprising a pair of outer cable conduit members each having a support bracket, wherein said support bracket is connected to said outer cable conduit member. 20. The system of claim 19, wherein said support bracket comprises: a pair of fastener arms each having a distal end terminating in a female clasp fastener; and a male clasp fastener connected to the outer cable conduit member; and wherein said pair of fastener arms are opposibly configured to each other to connect and reliably engage a corresponding pair of the male clasp fasteners, thereby fastening said support bracket to said outer cable conduit member of said structural member 21 . The system of claim 20, further comprising a proximate longitudinally extending member connected to said pair of fastener arms for connecting said support bracket to a building ceiling or to a connector therebetween, such as a wire. 22. The system of claim 21 , wherein a plurality of said structural support brackets are spaced intermittently along said longitudinal axis with a linear density corresponding to a structural grid of a standard drop ceiling. 23. The system of claim 22, wherein said structural support brackets are spaced intermittently along said longitudinal axis with a linear density range of one support bracket per 0.5 m to 2 m. 24. The system of claim 23, wherein a plurality of power supplies are mounted to said mounting slot, wherein each power supply is positioned adjacent to one of the structural support brackets. 25. The system of claim 1 wherein said heat sink has a heat sink surface area, wherein said heat sink surface area per unit length of said structural member is greater than or equal to 10 cm 2 /linear cm. 26. The system of claim 1 wherein said plurality of heat dissipating elements have a height, a bottom width, a top width. 27. The system of claim 26 wherein said plurality of heat dissipating elements have a ratio of height to an average width that is greater than or equal to 5:1 . 28. The system of claim 26 wherein said bottom width is greater than or equal to said top width. 29. The system of claim 1 , wherein said plurality of heat dissipating elements form a plurality of thermal passages having an average passage width that is greater than or equal to 1 mm and less than or equal to 1 cm. 30. The system of claim 1 , wherein said plurality of heat dissipating elements is greater than or equal to 3 and less than or equal to 20. 31 . The system of claim 26, wherein said plurality of heat dissipating elements comprise a pair of outer heat dissipating elements and a central plurality of heat dissipating elements positioned between said pair of outer heat dissipating elements, wherein said height of said central plurality of heat dissipating elements is greater than said height of said outer heat dissipating elements. 32. The system of claim 31 , further comprising an inner cable conduit member extending from said structural member top surface, said inner cable conduit member having a distal end with a mounting slot that extends into a region that is above at least a portion of said heat dissipating elements in said outer portion. 33. The system of claim 1 that is modular and configured to connect with additional systems to provide an extended length with continuous lighting over said extended length. 34. The system of claim 1 , wherein each system has a longitudinal length that is between about 0.5 m and 4 m. 35. The system of claim 2, wherein said optical light source comprises a light emitting diode (LED) module. 36. The system of claim 35, wherein said LED module comprises: a driver; an optical sensor; and a controller, wherein said driver, optical sensor and controller are electrically connected to provide a user-controlled illumination output. 37. The system of claim 36, further comprising an electrical wire positioned in a cable conduit for providing power to said LED module and any additional systems in modular connection with said system. 38. The system of claim 2 wherein said optical light sources have a linear density per unit of length of structural member of greater than or equal to 1 per cm. 39. The system of claim 38 wherein each optical light module comprises one or more LEDs, the optical light module providing radiant energy greater than or equal to 0.1 W. 40. The system of claim 1 further comprising a ceiling panel supported by surface support. 41 . The system of claim 40, wherein said ceiling panel is part of a drop ceiling. 42. The system of claim 41 , wherein said ceiling panel separates a first volume and a second volume, wherein said optical light source is positioned to illuminate said first volume and said heat sink is positioned in said second volume. 43. The system of claim 42 wherein said second volume corresponds to a ceiling volume defined between said ceiling panel and a ceiling that separates said second volume from an outer environment. 44. The system of claim 1 wherein said ceiling panel comprises an optically transparent material and is part of a greenhouse ceiling. 45. The system of claim 1 , wherein said surface support further comprises a clamp, a shelf, a joist, a bracket, a screw, a rivet, an adhesive, or a combination of these to connect a ceiling panel to said structural member. 46. The system of claim 1 , wherein the ceiling receiving panel slot extends from the structural member at an angle, configured to receive a correspondingly angled ceiling panel relative to the structural member. 47. The system of claim 46, further comprising a ceiling panel having a corrugated cross-sectional shape, with an angled outer portion postioned in the ceiling panel receiving slot. 48. The system of claim 46, wherein said ceiling panel comprises translucent or transparent polycarbonate. 49. A method of making a structurally integrateable lighting system said method comprising: providing a structural member comprising: a top surface , a bottom surface and a longitudinal axis, wherein the top surface is opposibly positioned relative to the bottom surface; 

 a heat sink comprising at least one heat dissipating element thermally connected to an inner portion of said structural member top surface and having a heat dissipating longitudinal axis; a support surface extending along an outer edge of said top surface wherein said heat dissipating longitudinal axis is substantially aligned with said structural member longitudinal axis; and attaching an optical light module having at least one optical light source to the bottom surface of the structural member. 50. The method of claim 49, further comprising a step of supporting a ceiling panel to the support surface or positioning an outer edge of a ceiling panel in a receiving slot of the structural member. 51 . The method of claim 50, further comprising a step of fastening the ceiling panel to the support surface. 52. The method of claim 50, wherein the support surface comprises a first support surface on a first outer edge of the top surface and a second support surface on a second outer edge, further comprising the steps of: supporting a first ceiling panel on the first support surface; and supporting a second ceiling panel on the second support surface. 53. The method of claim 52, comprising an array of aligned structurally integrateable lighting systems to support a drop ceiling. 54. The method of claim 52, comprising an array of aligned structurally integrateable lighting systems to support a greenhouse ceiling. 55. A method of illuminating a grow room by incorporating the structurally integrateable lighting system of any of claims 1 -48 into a grow room ceiling and powering the at least one optical light source. 56. A method of making a grow room by incorporating any of the structurally integrateable lighting systems of claims 1 -48 as structural elements to connect adjacent ceiling panels, wherein the ceiling panels comprise: optically transparent ceiling panels as part of a greenhouse; or optically opaque ceiling panels as part of a drop ceiling.
